Screen myScreen, *pScreen = &myScreen;
auto s = myScreen.*cursor;

Exercise 19.14: Is the following code legal? If so, what does it do? If not,
why?
auto pmf = &Screen::get_cursor;
pmf = &Screen::get;

Answer:
The code is not legal since pointer to member functions require the same return type but
get_cursor and get have different return types.

Exercise 19.15: What is the difference between an ordinary function pointer
and a pointer to a member function?

Answer:
Ordinary function pointer points to a standalone function while a pointer to member function points
to a class member and can be called only on an object of that class.

